<p>Hi I have following 2 files in <code>a.c</code> I have</p>  <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;  int i; static int j; int main() {         printf("i = %d\n",i);         printf("j = %d\n",j);         return 0; } </code></pre>  <p>and in <code>b.c</code> I have</p>  <pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;  extern int i=2; extern int j=5; </code></pre>  <p>In this example when I run, I get answer as 2,0 but complier throws warning <code>initialized and declared ‘extern’</code> for both variables.</p>  <p>How b.c is able to access <code>j</code> and not throws error since scope of <code>j</code> is for <code>a.c</code> only?</p>